\fIhash of array input\fR
.IX Subsection "hash of array input"
.PP
.Vb 6
\& $test_data = summary(
\&     {
\&         A => runif(9),
\&         B => runif(9)
\&     },
\& );
.Ve
.SS t_test
.IX Subsection "t_test"
There are 1\-sample and 2\-sample t\-tests, from one or two arrays:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& my $t_test = t_test( $array1, mu => 0.2334 );
.Ve
.PP
or 2\-sample:
.PP
.Vb 4
\& $t_test = t_test(
\&     $array1,    $array2,
\&     paired => 1
\& );
.Ve
.PP
returns a hash reference, which looks like:
.PP
.Vb 7
\& conf_int     => [
\&     \-0.06672889, 0.25672889
\& ],
\& df        => 5,
\& estimate  => 0.095,
\& p_value   => 0.19143688433660,
\& statistic => 1.50996688705414
.Ve
.PP
the two groups compared can be specified, though not necessarily, as \f(CW\*(C`x\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`y\*(C'\fR, just like in R:
.PP
.Vb 4
\& $t_test = t_test(
\&     \*(Aqx\*(Aq => $array1, \*(Aqy\*(Aq => $array2,
\&     paired => 1
\& );
.Ve
.PP
\fIParameters\fR
.IX Subsection "Parameters"
.PP
\fIReturn Hash\fR
.IX Subsection "Return Hash"
.SS transpose
.IX Subsection "transpose"
Transposes a two\-dimensional data structure, swapping rows and columns. Accepts either an array of arrays or a hash of hashes.
Returns a new reference of the same type; the input is never modified.
.PP
\fIArray of array input\fR
.IX Subsection "Array of array input"
.PP
Takes a reference to an array of array references and returns a new AoA where \f(CW\*(C`output[j][i] = input[i][j]\*(C'\fR.
.PP
.Vb 5
\& my $matrix = [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]];
\& my $t = transpose($matrix);
\& # [[1, 4],
\& #  [2, 5],
\& #  [3, 6]]
.Ve
.PP
All rows must be the same length; a ragged input is a fatal error.
\&\f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR is valid as an element value and is preserved exactly. An empty outer array or an array of empty rows both return \f(CW\*(C`[]\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Dies if:
\&\- any inner element is not an array reference
\&\- rows differ in length (ragged array)
.PP
\fIHash of hash input\fR
.IX Subsection "Hash of hash input"
.PP
Takes a reference to a hash of hash references and returns a new HoH where \f(CW\*(C`output{col}{row} = input{row}{col}\*(C'\fR.
.PP
.Vb 4
\& my $table = { alice => { score => 97, grade => \*(AqA\*(Aq }, bob   => { score => 84, grade => \*(AqB\*(Aq } };
\& my $t = transpose($table);
\& # { score => { alice => 97,  bob => 84  },
\& #   grade => { alice => \*(AqA\*(Aq, bob => \*(AqB\*(Aq } }
.Ve
.PP
Inner keys do not need to be uniform across rows. If a given column key appears in only some rows, the output hash for that column will simply contain only those rows — no padding or \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR\-filling is performed.
.PP
.Vb 3
\& my $sparse = {
\& a => { x => 1, y => 2 },
\& b => { x => 3, z => 4 } };
\& 
\& my $t = transpose($sparse);
\& # { x => { a => 1, b => 3 },
\& #   y => { a => 2 },
\& #   z => { b => 4 } }
.Ve
.PP
An empty outer hash or an outer hash whose inner hashes are all empty both return \f(CW\*(C`{}\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Dies if any inner element is not a hash reference
.SS value_counts
.IX Subsection "value_counts"
Count the values in a given data set, return a hash reference showing how many times each particular value is present.
.PP
\fIScalar\fR
.IX Subsection "Scalar"
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $hash = value_counts(\*(Aqc\*(Aq);
.Ve
.PP
returns \f(CW\*(C`{ c => 1 }\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fIArray reference\fR
.IX Subsection "Array reference"
.PP
.Vb 1
\& value_counts([\*(Aqa\*(Aq,\*(Aqb\*(Aq,\*(Aqb\*(Aq]);
.Ve
.PP
returns \f(CW\*(C`{ a => 1, b => 2}\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fIArray\fR
.IX Subsection "Array"
.PP
.Vb 1
\& my $value_counts = value_counts(\*(Aqa\*(Aq,\*(Aqb\*(Aq,\*(Aqb\*(Aq);
.Ve
.PP
like an array reference above, returns \f(CW\*(C`{ a => 1, b => 2}\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fIHash\fR
.IX Subsection "Hash"
.PP
.Vb 1
\& my $value_counts = value_counts( { A => \*(Aqa\*(Aq, B => \*(Aqa\*(Aq, C => \*(Aqb\*(Aq } );
.Ve
.PP
returns \f(CW\*(C`{ a => 2, b => 1}\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fIHash of array\fR
.IX Subsection "Hash of array"
.PP
.Vb 1
\& my $value_counts = value_counts({ \*(Aqa\*(Aq => [\*(Aqj\*(Aq, \*(Aqt\*(Aq, \*(Aqt\*(Aq], \*(Aqb\*(Aq => [\*(Aqj\*(Aq, \*(Aqt\*(Aq, \*(Aqv\*(Aq]});
.Ve
.PP
without a key (like above), the occurences of \f(CW\*(C`j\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`t\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`v\*(C'\fR are counted.
.PP
With a key, like \f(CW\*(C`a\*(C'\fR for above, only values within that hash key are counted:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& my $vc = value_counts({ \*(Aqa\*(Aq => [\*(Aqj\*(Aq, \*(Aqt\*(Aq, \*(Aqt\*(Aq], \*(Aqb\*(Aq => [\*(Aqj\*(Aq, \*(Aqt\*(Aq, \*(Aqv\*(Aq]}, \*(Aqa\*(Aq);
.Ve
.PP
\fIHash of hash (table)\fR
.IX Subsection "Hash of hash (table)"
.PP
.Vb 12
\& $hash = value_counts( {
\&     A => {
\&         a => \*(Aqx\*(Aq,
\&         b => \*(Aqz\*(Aq
\&     },
\&     B => {
\&         a => \*(Aqx\*(Aq
\&     },
\&     C => {
\&         a => \*(Aqy\*(Aq
\&     }
\& }, \*(Aqa\*(Aq);
.Ve
.PP
the column, or second hash key, that you wish to count, is specified at the command line
.SS var
.IX Subsection "var"
as simple as possible:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& var(2, 4, 5, 8, 9)
.Ve
.PP
as of version 0.02, \f(CW\*(C`var\*(C'\fR will die if any undefined values are provided
.PP
like \f(CW\*(C`min\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`max\*(C'\fR, etc., \f(CW\*(C`var\*(C'\fR can accept array references, to make code simpler:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& my $ref = \e@arr;
\& var($ref) = var(@arr)
.Ve
.SS var_test
.IX Subsection "var_test"
As described by R: Performs an F test to compare the variances of two samples from normal populations
.PP
.Vb 1
\& use Stats::LikeR;
\& 
\& my @x = (2.9, 3.0, 2.5, 2.6, 3.2);
\& my @y = (3.8, 2.7, 4.0, 2.4);
\& 
\& my $vt = var_test(\e@x, \e@y);
.Ve
.PP
also, conf_level can be set:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $vt = var_test(\e@x, \e@y, conf_level => 0.99);
.Ve
.PP
as well as a ratio (from R: the hypothesized ratio of the population variances of \f(CW\*(C`x\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`y\*(C'\fR:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $test_data = var_test(\e@xk, \e@yk, ratio => 2);
.Ve
.SS wilcox_test
.IX Subsection "wilcox_test"
.Vb 4
\& $test_data = wilcox_test(
\&     [1.83,  0.50,  1.62,  2.48, 1.68, 1.88, 1.55, 3.06, 1.30],
\&     [0.878, 0.647, 0.598, 2.05, 1.06, 1.29, 1.06, 3.14, 1.29]
\& );
.Ve
.PP
It fully supports paired tests (\f(CW\*(C`paired => 1\*(C'\fR) and can calculate exact p\-values (the default for \f(CW\*(C`N < 50\*(C'\fR without ties). If ties are encountered, it automatically switches to an approximation with continuity correction.
.SS write_table
.IX Subsection "write_table"
mimics R\*(Aqs \f(CW\*(C`write.table\*(C'\fR, with data as first argument to subroutine, and output file as second
.PP
.Vb 1
\& write_table(\e@data_aoh, $tmp_file, sep => "\et", \*(Aqrow.names\*(Aq => 1);
.Ve
.PP
You can also precisely filter and reorder which columns are written by passing an array reference to \f(CW\*(C`col.names\*(C'\fR:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& write_table(\e@data, $tmp_file, sep => "\et", \*(Aqcol.names\*(Aq => [\*(Aqc\*(Aq, \*(Aqa\*(Aq]);
.Ve
.PP
undefined variables are printed as \f(CW\*(C`NA\*(C'\fR by default, but can be set as you wish using \f(CW\*(C`undef.val\*(C'\fR
.PP
.Vb 1
\& write_table(\e%data_hoa, \*(Aq/tmp/undef.val.tsv\*(Aq, sep => "\et", \*(Aqundef.val\*(Aq => \*(Aqnan\*(Aq)
.Ve
.PP
as of version 0.07, \f(CW\*(C`write_table\*(C'\fR determines comma and tab\-separated delimiters from the filename, but will override if \f(CW\*(C`sep\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`delim\*(C'\fR are explicitly set.
.PP
Args can also be accepted:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& write_table( \*(Aqdata\*(Aq => \e%flat, \*(Aqfile\*(Aq => $f );
.Ve
